<commentary id="fs-id1167065820258">
<title>Discussion for (a)</title>
<para id="fs-id1167065926897">This small value for the capacitance indicates how difficult it is to make a device with a large capacitance. Special techniques help, such as using very-large-area thin foils placed close together or using a dielectric (to be discussed below).</para>
</commentary>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167066121708"><label/>
<problem id="fs-id1167065859214">
<note id="fs-id1167065945180">
<label/><title>Strategy FOR (B)</title>
<para id="fs-id1167065733568">Knowing <emphasis effect="italics">C</emphasis>, find the charge stored by solving the equation  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math>, for the charge <emphasis effect="italics">Q</emphasis>.</para>
</note>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167065876762">
<label/>
<title>Solution for (b)</title>
<para id="fs-id1167066138031">The charge <emphasis effect="italics">Q</emphasis> on the capacitor is</para>
<equation id="fs-id1164567967992"> <m:math display="block">
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mtable>
   <m:mtr rowalign="center">
    <m:mtd rowalign="center" columnalign="right">
     <m:mi>Q</m:mi>
    </m:mtd>
    <m:mtd rowalign="center">
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    </m:mtd>
    <m:mtd rowalign="center" columnalign="left">
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mi>V</m:mi>
     </m:mrow>
    </m:mtd>
   </m:mtr>
   <m:mtr rowalign="center">
    <m:mtd rowalign="center"/>
    <m:mtd rowalign="center">
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    </m:mtd>
    <m:mtd rowalign="center" columnalign="left">
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo>
       <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>8.9</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
         <m:mrow>
          <m:mn>10</m:mn>
         </m:mrow>
         <m:mrow>
          <m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>9</m:mn>
         </m:mrow>
        </m:msup>
        <m:mtext>F</m:mtext>
       </m:mrow>
      <m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo>
       <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>3.00</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
         <m:mrow>
          <m:mn>10</m:mn>
         </m:mrow>
         <m:mn>3</m:mn>
        </m:msup>
        <m:mtext>V</m:mtext>
       </m:mrow>
      <m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow>
     </m:mrow>
    </m:mtd>
   </m:mtr>
   <m:mtr rowalign="center">
    <m:mtd rowalign="center"/>
    <m:mtd rowalign="center">
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    </m:mtd>
    <m:mtd rowalign="center" columnalign="left">
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>2.7</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
       <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>10</m:mn>
       </m:mrow>
       <m:mrow>
        <m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>5</m:mn>
       </m:mrow>
      </m:msup>
      <m:mtext>C</m:mtext>
     </m:mrow>
<m:mtext>.</m:mtext>
    </m:mtd>
   </m:mtr>

  </m:mtable>
 </m:mrow>
</m:math> </equation>

</solution>
<commentary id="fs-id1167064899879">
<title>Discussion for (b)</title>
<para id="fs-id1167065852280">This charge is only slightly greater than typical static electricity charges. More charge could be stored by using a dielectric between the capacitor plates.</para>
</commentary>
</exercise></note><note id="fs-id1167065884590" class="worked-example"><title>What battery is needed to charge a capacitor?</title>

<exercise id="fs-id1167065874914" class="18-ex106 unnumbered">
<label/>
<problem id="fs-id1167065893597">
<para id="fs-id1167065880157">Your friend provides you with a  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mtext>F</m:mtext>
 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  capacitor. To store  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mn>120</m:mn><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mtext>C</m:mtext>
 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  on this capacitor, what voltage battery should you buy?</para>

<note id="fs-id1167065847522">
<label/><title>Strategy</title>
<para id="fs-id1167065953302">Use the equation  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  to find the voltage needed to charge the capacitor.
</para>
</note>
</problem>

<solution id="fs-id1167062401500">
<label/>
<title>Solution</title>
<para id="fs-id1167064546113">Solving  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  for the voltage gives  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>V</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mo>/</m:mo><m:mi>C</m:mi></m:mrow>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math> . Inserting  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mtext>F</m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>10</m:mn>
   </m:mrow>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>−6</m:mn>
   </m:mrow>
  </m:msup>
  <m:mtext>F</m:mtext>
 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  and  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>120</m:mn><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mtext>C</m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>120</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>10</m:mn>
   </m:mrow>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>−6</m:mn>
   </m:mrow>
  </m:msup>
  <m:mtext>C</m:mtext>
 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  gives</para><equation id="fs-id1164565974557"> <m:math display="block">
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mi>V</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac>
   <m:mi>Q</m:mi>
   <m:mi>C</m:mi>
  </m:mfrac>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>120</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>−6</m:mn></m:mrow>
    </m:msup>
    <m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>−6</m:mn></m:mrow>
    </m:msup>
    <m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>12</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.3em"/><m:mtext>V</m:mtext></m:mrow>
</m:math> </equation></solution>

<commentary id="fs-id1167065826885">
<title>Discussion</title>
<para id="fs-id1167066091154">Such a battery should be easy to procure. There is still a question of whether the battery contains enough energy to provide the desired charge. The equation  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:msub>
   <m:mi>U</m:mi>
   <m:mi>E</m:mi>
  </m:msub>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mstyle scriptlevel="+1">
   <m:mfrac>
    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
   </m:mfrac>
  </m:mstyle>
  <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:msup>
   <m:mi>V</m:mi>
   <m:mn>2</m:mn>
  </m:msup>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math>  allows us to calculate the required energy.</para>
<equation id="fs-id1164567639273"> <m:math display="block">
 <m:mrow>
  <m:msub>
   <m:mi>U</m:mi>
   <m:mi>E</m:mi>
  </m:msub>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac>
   <m:mn>1</m:mn>
   <m:mn>2</m:mn>
  </m:mfrac>
  <m:mi>C</m:mi><m:msup>
   <m:mi>V</m:mi>
   <m:mn>2</m:mn>
  </m:msup>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac>
   <m:mn>1</m:mn>
   <m:mn>2</m:mn>
  </m:mfrac>
  <m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:mrow>
    </m:msup>
    <m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mrow>
  <m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:msup>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo>
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>12</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.3em"/><m:mtext>V</m:mtext></m:mrow>
    <m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow>
   <m:mn>2</m:mn>
  </m:msup>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>72</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.3em"/><m:mtext>mJ</m:mtext></m:mrow>
</m:math> </equation><para id="fs-id1167064770196">A typical commercial battery can easily provide this much energy.</para>
</commentary>
</exercise>
</note></section>
